
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `gdm-screenshot` baraye gereftan ax az safhe login (login screen) dar Linux estefade mishavad, vaghti ke shoma az GDM (GNOME Display Manager) estefade mikonid. In dastoor aks ra zakhire mikonad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `--file filename.png` --> 🖼️  Esme file ax ra tayin mikonad. Agar esm tayin nashavad, esme pishfarz estefade mishavad.
    🔹 `--destination /path/to/directory` --> 📁 Mahale zakhire kardane ax ra moshakhas mikonad. Agar in gozine estefade nashavad, directory pishfarz estefade mishavad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ gdm-screenshot

    🔹  Gereftan ax az safhe vorood va zakhire kardan an ba esme pishfarz dar directory pishfarz.

    $ gdm-screenshot --file login_screen.png --destination /tmp

    🔹  Gereftan ax az safhe vorood va zakhire kardan an ba esme `login_screen.png` dar pooshe `/tmp`.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ gdm-screenshot --file mylogin.png

    🔹  Ax az safhe login gerefte va ba esme `mylogin.png` dar directory pishfarz zakhire mishavad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `gdm-screenshot` command is used to take a screenshot of the login screen in Linux when you are using GDM (GNOME Display Manager). It saves the screenshot to a file.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `--file filename.png` --> 🖼️ Specifies the filename for the screenshot. If no filename is provided, a default name is used.
    🔹 `--destination /path/to/directory` --> 📁 Specifies the destination directory for the screenshot. If this option is not used, the default directory is used.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ gdm-screenshot

    🔹  Takes a screenshot of the login screen and saves it with a default name in the default directory.

    $ gdm-screenshot --file login_screen.png --destination /tmp

    🔹  Takes a screenshot of the login screen and saves it as `login_screen.png` in the `/tmp` directory.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ gdm-screenshot --file mylogin.png

    🔹  Takes a screenshot of the login screen and saves it as `mylogin.png` in the default directory.
